2.4 Problem statement
Large language models and agentic systems are beginning to participate in economic processes in ways that are consequential but poorly understood. They shape decisions, generate information, mediate interactions, and may increasingly act on behalf of users or organizations. As a result, they are not only tools of production and analysis, but also objects of economic study.
The current field is moving quickly, but several problems remain:

the behavior of agents is often treated as stable or generic when it may vary substantially across architectures, prompting regimes, and deployment contexts;
the economic preferences and decision-making patterns of agents are still poorly understood;
agent-to-agent interaction may generate emergent system-level outcomes that are not obvious from studying single models in isolation;
human-agent interaction raises questions about trust, perception, bias, and representation;
methodological standards for reproducibility, benchmarking, and interpretation remain weak in many parts of the literature.

The lab exists to address these gaps through rigorous, public-facing research.

2.5 Why a nonprofit
The nonprofit structure is appropriate because the lab is intended to produce public-benefit research rather than private commercial products or private-client services. Its goal is to generate knowledge, improve research quality, train students through participation in research, and contribute methods, benchmarks, datasets, and findings that are broadly useful to researchers, educators, policymakers, and the public.
The lab is not intended to operate as:

a consulting business;
a software product company;
a startup incubator;
a paid private-client research shop.

The nonprofit form supports independence, public dissemination, student engagement, and credibility with academic, philanthropic, and public-interest funders.

2.6 Core research areas

2.6.1 1. Agents as objects of research
The lab studies AI agents themselves as objects of inquiry. This includes:

economic preferences;
decision-making processes;
revealed versus stated preferences;
inherent and contextual biases;
differences across architectures and prompting conditions.

This area is motivated by the idea that agents may display systematic patterns of choice and bias that must be understood before they can be used reliably in research or economic settings.


2.6.2 2. Agent-to-agent interaction
The lab studies how AI agents behave in agentic economies and multi-agent systems. This includes:

negotiation;
coordination;
competition;
market-like interaction;
price formation and other emergent outcomes.

The focus is not only on individual agent behavior, but also on how interaction produces system-level effects.


2.6.3 3. Human-agent interaction
The lab studies how humans perceive, evaluate, trust, and respond to AI agents, especially where the agent economy overlaps with the human economy. This includes:

acceptance of AI systems in decision environments;
perception of AI-generated content;
trust in AI versus human advisors;
representational and demographic concerns in how people respond to agents.

This line of work is especially important as AI systems become more visible in labor, communication, and service settings.


2.6.4 4. Methodology, benchmarks, and research quality
The lab develops rigorous methodologies for studying agents and human-agent systems in a field that is growing quickly but often lacks consistency and reproducibility. This includes:

benchmark design;
experimental methodology;
replication and reproducibility standards;
better ways to identify and interpret bias;
methods for comparing agent behavior to human behavior.

This work is central to the lab’s public-benefit value. The lab is not only producing findings, but helping define how the field should study these questions well.

2.7 Who the lab serves
The lab’s work is intended to benefit:

researchers in economics, behavioral science, AI, and adjacent fields;
students who want to participate in rigorous AI-related research;
policymakers and institutions trying to understand the social and economic effects of AI agents;
journalists, educators, and public audiences seeking credible research and interpretation;
philanthropic and public-interest organizations supporting responsible AI research.

2.8 What the lab produces
The lab is expected to produce:

academic papers and working papers;
public research summaries and explainers;
datasets and benchmarks where appropriate;
methodological notes and reproducibility guidance;
lectures, workshops, and public events;
student-engaged research opportunities.

2.11 Collaboration strategy
The lab should collaborate with both academia and industry, but it should be careful about how those collaborations are framed.

2.11.1 Academic collaborations
Academic collaborations are a natural fit because they support:

rigor;
peer review;
student involvement;
dissemination through established research channels.



2.11.2 Industry collaborations
Industry collaboration may be valuable because frontier knowledge about agentic systems is often concentrated inside companies building and deploying them. Such collaborations can improve empirical relevance and access to real-world contexts.
However, the lab should state clearly that:

collaborations must preserve research independence;
private firms should not control conclusions or publication decisions;
the lab is not conducting paid private-client research;
sponsorship should support public-interest research rather than private commercial advantage.

2.12 Student engagement
Student participation should be treated as a core feature, not a side benefit.
Students may participate as:

research assistants;
fellows;
volunteers;
workshop participants;
coauthors where appropriate.

This strengthens the lab’s educational mission and provides a clear answer to why the work belongs in a nonprofit setting.

2.13 Fundraising narrative
The strongest fundraising case is not simply that AI is important. It is that the emerging agent economy is economically significant, methodologically underdeveloped, and in need of independent public-interest research.
The lab’s funding narrative should emphasize:

independent research on a rapidly growing and socially important domain;
rigorous methodology in an area where standards are still forming;
educational value through student engagement;
public dissemination of findings;
the need for noncommercial, credible analysis of systems with broad economic effects.

6.3 Role summary

6.3.1 Directors
Directors are expected to:

attend and participate in board decisions;
review and approve major organizational actions;
support legal and ethical compliance;
help protect the corporation’s mission and nonprofit status.



6.3.2 President
The President is expected to:

oversee execution of board-approved actions;
help coordinate the organization’s activities;
sign documents and filings as authorized.



6.3.3 Secretary
The Secretary is expected to:

maintain minutes and records;
help ensure notices and formal records are kept properly;
maintain the corporation’s organizational documents.



6.3.4 Treasurer
The Treasurer is expected to:

oversee basic financial recordkeeping and financial reporting;
help review budgets, bank arrangements, and financial controls;
support compliance with filing and financial oversight obligations.

10.3 3. Conflict of interest
A conflict of interest exists when a covered person has a direct or indirect financial interest, personal interest, or organizational loyalty that may interfere with the person’s ability to act solely in the best interests of the corporation.
Examples include:

ownership or compensation interest in an entity doing business with the corporation;
family relationship with a person receiving compensation or economic benefit from the corporation;
personal benefit from a grant, contract, publication arrangement, or vendor selection;
research or consulting ties that could affect the independence of the corporation’s work.

10.6 6. Approval standard
The Board may approve the transaction only if:

the material facts have been fully disclosed;
disinterested directors determine in good faith that the transaction is in the corporation’s best interests;
the transaction is fair and reasonable;
comparable alternatives have been considered where appropriate;
the decision is documented in the minutes.

10.8 8. Annual statements
Each covered person shall annually sign a statement affirming that the person:

received a copy of this policy;
read and understands the policy;
agrees to comply with the policy; and
understands that the corporation must operate in a manner consistent with its charitable and tax-exempt purposes.

10.10 10. Records
The minutes of Board and committee meetings shall contain:

the name of the person who disclosed or was found to have a conflict;
the nature of the conflict;
the action taken to determine whether a conflict existed;
the final decision and vote.

11.2 Scope
This policy applies to compensation for:

officers;
directors if ever compensated;
key employees;
contractors with insider relationships;
any person who may be a disqualified person for federal tax purposes.

11.3 Approval standards
Before approving compensation, the Board or an authorized committee composed only of disinterested persons should:

review the duties of the position;
obtain comparability data where practical, such as salary surveys, peer nonprofit compensation, or independent quotes;
determine that the proposed compensation is reasonable and in the best interests of the corporation;
document the basis for the decision in contemporaneous minutes.

11.5 Documentation
The minutes should reflect:

who was considered;
who voted;
what comparability data was reviewed;
the approved amount and effective date;
any abstentions or recusals.

11.6 Frequency
Compensation should be reviewed:

before initial approval;
upon material role changes;
periodically thereafter.

12.2 Activity 1. Research on agents as objects of study
The organization studies AI agents themselves as objects of educational and scientific research. This includes research on the preferences, decision-making patterns, and biases of large language models and related agentic systems, as well as differences across architectures, prompting conditions, and deployment contexts.
Activities may include:

designing and conducting experiments involving language models and agentic systems;
comparing revealed and stated preferences in language models;
studying bias, preference formation, and decision-making behavior across models;
preparing papers, research memoranda, and methodological materials for public dissemination.

Representative current or near-term work includes Model Personality Trumps Persona Prompting: Evidence from Controlled Prompting Experiments and related research on preferences, behavior, and methodological interpretation.
This activity is expected to account for approximately 35 percent of the organization’s time and resources in the first year. It will be conducted primarily by directors, collaborating academic colleagues, and student researchers.

12.3 Activity 2. Research on agent-to-agent interaction and the emerging agent economy
The organization studies how AI agents interact with one another and how these interactions may produce system-level outcomes in an emerging agent economy. The educational and scientific purpose of this work is to improve understanding of how agent behavior scales from individual systems to interactive and market-like environments.
Activities may include:

conceptual and empirical work on agent-to-agent interaction;
development of research agendas, benchmarks, and datasets related to multi-agent systems;
simulations, negotiation environments, and other structured interaction settings;
preparation of agenda-setting papers and public research outputs on LLMs as economic agents.

Representative topics include price formation in multi-agent language-model markets, repeated negotiation games, and the evolution of strategy and knowledge in multi-agent settings.
This activity is expected to account for approximately 30 percent of the organization’s time and resources in the first year. It will be conducted primarily by directors and academic collaborators.

12.4 Activity 3. Research on human-agent interaction and public perception
The organization studies how humans perceive, evaluate, trust, and respond to AI agents and AI-generated outputs, especially as the agent economy increasingly overlaps with the human economy. This research advances educational and scientific purposes by contributing evidence about human interaction with emerging technologies and the social interpretation of agent behavior.
Activities may include:

pilot studies and experiments involving human subjects, subject to appropriate review and approval where required;
research design, survey development, and literature review;
analysis of how different populations perceive and engage with agents;
public dissemination of findings through papers, lectures, workshops, and research summaries.

Representative current or near-term work includes AI or Not? Human Inability to Reliably Detect AI-Generated Content and related work on trust, acceptance, and response to AI systems.
This activity is expected to account for approximately 20 percent of the organization’s time and resources in the first year. It will be conducted primarily by directors and student researchers, including pilot work and experimental preparation.

12.5 Activity 4. Methodology, benchmarks, and research quality
The organization develops methodologies, benchmarks, and reproducibility-oriented research practices for studying language models and AI agents. This is a central public-benefit function because the field is expanding quickly and often lacks shared standards for replication, interpretation, and comparison across systems.
Activities may include:

methodological papers and replication-oriented studies;
benchmark development;
guidance on reproducibility, inference configuration, and experimental design;
educational materials that improve research practice in the field.

This activity will be carried out across the organization’s substantive research areas and is expected to overlap with each of the activities above.
